column1: Before 1 July 2020, will the Chilean government pass legislation that caps administrative fees and/or operating profits of the country's pension fund managers?

column6: 1st July seems a bit difficult at the moment.
Before 1 July 2020, will the Chilean government pass legislation that caps administrative fees and/or operating profits of the country's pension fund managers? Reducing my forecast by 100%.

Before 1 July 2020, will the Chilean government pass legislation that caps administrative fees and/or operating profits of the country's pension fund managers? Hattip for a great analysis to @dlaiocean, who brought me back to reality.

Read Ministra Schmidt's statements in todays La Tercera, and draw your own conclusions. https://www.latercera.com/pulso/noticia/no-podemos-descuidar-las-pensiones-del-futuro-ministra-zaldivar-reacciona-propuesta-mesa-tecnica-la-oposicion/972886/
Lets examine the facts before forecasting this question.

Before 1 July 2020, will the Chilean government pass legislation that caps administrative fees and/or operating profits of the country's pension fund managers? On second thought, the only victims here are the financial funds and it's "doing something".

Before 1 July 2020, will the Chilean government pass legislation that caps administrative fees and/or operating profits of the country's pension fund managers? This just doesn't appear to be feasible, regardless of how emotionially satisfying it may appear.
What if it only applies to FONASA?

No real knowledge here - just assuming this is unlikely, but no so unlikely that the question wouldn't be asked.

While a full nationalization is unlikely prior to 1 July, this initiative could gain support as an additional stop-gap prior to negotiations for a new constitution. Efforts to address the unrest thus far have been unsuccessful, but the President could push for such a measure to improve his approval ratings as the country moves toward reform.

The argument is that there is a problem with contributions. Fees and operating profits are not transparent, and it doesn't solve the problem of low pensions. I don't think they will move to do this, particularly in this time period.
